        </div>
    </nav>

    <div class="container">
        <h2 class="section-header">About My Internship</h2>
        
        <div class="cms-panel">
            <h3 style="margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem;">Role: Full Stack Development Intern</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: #d4d4d8;">
               Role: Full Stack Development Intern

During my internship, I focused on understanding how a web application works end-to-end by building a Content Management System (CMS) from scratch instead of relying on tools like WordPress.

I implemented a Node.js and Express backend to handle routing, form submissions, and basic request handling. Using EJS, I worked on rendering dynamic content on the frontend and structuring reusable templates.

To understand application flow clearly, I built CRUD functionality using an in-memory data structure before integrating any database. This helped me learn how data moves between client, server, and views.

On the frontend, I designed a dark-themed UI using pure CSS, focusing on layout, spacing, and responsiveness instead of depending on frameworks.

This project represents my approach to learning by building and improving through hands-on practice rather than only studying theory.
            </p>
            <br>
            <h3 style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">Core Responsibilities & Achievements:</h3>
            <ul style="color: var(--text-secondary); margin-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8;">
                <li>Architected a Node.js and Express backend capable of handling RESTful routes.</li>
                <li>Designed a dynamic templating engine workflow using EJS to inject server-side data into the client views.</li>
                <li>Built an administrative dashboard with protected routes simulating authentication.</li>
                <li>Created a premium, responsive UI from scratch utilizing advanced CSS methodologies, avoiding heavy frameworks to ensure deep comprehension of styling mechanics.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>